title: For Sale:  Mossberg Over Under 12 gauge Silver Reserve NIB never shot
postcontent: Here is Mossberg International’s crowning achievement, the Silver Reserve Over and Under Shotgun. Examination of its lines and workmanship demonstrate the impressive expertise of Turkish Gunmakers who, after all, have been at the trade for as long as their Italian teachers and counterparts. Not only Mossberg, but also Remington, Smith & Wesson, and Weatherby have all indulged their lines with shotguns made in Turkey; and this is the most attractive of the entire lot. The Silver Reserve Field, of which this is a specimen, is equipped with five interchangeable choke tubes and wrench, providing the ultimate in versatility with lead, steel and other non-toxic loads. Manufacturer is Kayhan Art, or Khan, of Konya, Turkey. Importer is Mossberg International of New Haven, CT. Mossberg Int’l SKU is 75410. At the heart of every Reserve Series Over-and-Under is an underlock design, box lock action for superior strength and low profile. So says Mossberg. The photos show the attractively blued barrel, 3 inch chambered 28 inch Vent Rib with a total of five Benelli/Beretta thread choke tubes: two each .708 Improved Cylinder; and one each .701 Modified, one each .691 Improved Modified, and one each .683 Full. Stock and forend are satin finished European Walnut with cut checkering. Receiver is engraved satin nickel with gold inlay. Trigger is gold plated, and the tang safety serves as barrel selector. Barrels have single block extractor, and the extractor and chamber sides are nicely jeweled. Buttstock measures for a 14 inch length of pull including the Decelerator type buttpad; 1 1/2 inch drop at comb and 2 1/4 inch drop at heel with about a 3 degree right hand cant from the frame,  Weight empty is a well balanced 7.7 pounds with center of gravity at the back of the forend. Firing selection is by mechanical transfer, not by recoil.  These Silver Reserves command prices upwards of $650.00 at Gander PLUS Tax..... I would like $575 for this one with the extra chokes , original box. I am not a trap shooter, just a varmint slayer so dead rabbit or crow does not warrant an expensive gun like this

title: For Sale:  Ultra Compact Adjustable Stock (UCAS) - MP5 style stock similar to NEA PDW or M231 stock
postcontent:
After having searched for a stock like this some time with little success except for a few very overpriced options, I finally approached a manufacturer to see just what was possible.  Ultimately, this stock is what we landed on. You can see how this stock looks in the pic of my SBR below. 

Enabling the stock to function properly is a very short buffer assembly that allows for a buffer tube of just 3"-4".  I have always used and recommended the Gen 1 buffer assembly made by GSE Inc.  At this point, I do not maintain a large inventory on hand and this posting is essentially a way to test the market in order to determine if there is sufficient demand to justify pursuing further.  

Up until recently, I had included the buffer assembly with purchase, simply factoring in that additional cost and ordering the assembly.  However, having had a number of individuals commit to purchase, only to no-show or go MIA once I had received both their stock and buffer assembly, I am no longer including the buffer assembly with the purchase of the stock.  Instead, I am providing prospective buyers with the link to GSE's buffer assembly and leaving the acquisition of that item up to the buyer.  This reduces my exposure and allows for those who may know of and/or favor an alternative buffer system to go that route instead.  GSE also has a Gen 2 buffer assembly that is very nice and also works well with this stock, but due to the cost and the fact that it requires their custom shortened BCG, I have tended to favor their Gen 1 buffer assembly.  The links below will direct you to both of these.

http://www.gunsmokeenterprises.net/product.sc?productId=3&categoryId=2
http://www.gunsmokeenterprises.net/product.sc?productId=5&categoryId=2

Should the demand for this stock prove to be sufficient to continue, I would certainly anticipate that we either develop our own shortened 3"-4" buffer assembly in-house, or at the very least, approach GSE Inc. in order to try to negotiate some sort of pricing agreement.  If you know of other buffer assemblies that may work with this stock or if you have questions about a specific alternative, please let me know.

Included with purchase is the stock, castle nut, receiver end plate, two different sized shoulder rests. Regarding the two shoulder rests that may be attached to the stock, one is larger one and the other is just over half that size small (very similar in size to that of the NEA). The larger one is pictured on my SBR while the smaller one may be pictured in other pics or I’m happy to provide additional photos. 

Please contact me if you're interested or if you would like any additional information about this stock, potential buffer systems, or other similar stocks. I'm happy to ship within the U.S.

title: For Sale/Trade:  New Price Russian SKS 1951 Tula as issued unfired unrearsenaled
postcontent: All matching serial numbers on metal and stock. Seeing unfired condition didn't want to lower collectability by shooting it because I have other shooters and enjoy shooting them.I have done a lot of research on sites like Yooper John's and many claim unfired unrearsenaled but are not.I am convinced by details like no XXXXX'd out serial number on stock and not a force matched stock ,no square with line thru it symbol on receiver cover or stock(which would indicate rearsenaled),bright and shiney bayonet,bright bolt and bolt carrier with no powder residue,no powder residue on gas rod,traces of cosmoline still apparent on bolt face and other places,clean matching serial number strikes on all metal parts,unmolested inspection symbols and numbers on wood stock,number 1 struck on front of front sight base indicates best accuracy rating for the barrel's rifling,and solid wood buttstock and handguards like original( not laminated stock which all rearsenaled guns have).All these details ,missing in most all  Rusky's out there on the market,convince me this is the real deal and will only go up in price.Russian SKS's like this are a very very small percentage of the guns which have been imported over the years.Do the research,this is the holy grail of collectable SKS's.More photos to show some of these details on request.

title: For Sale:  1938 Ishevsk Mosin Nagant 91/30
postcontent:
Since I bought my Mosin Nagant M44 carbine, I no longer shoot my 91/30.  The carbine shoulders better for me and is generally a better fit.  

The rifle is in decent condition with all matching serial numbers. Pre-war 1938 vintage with round receiver.  The stock is solid and has no cracks.  The rifling is strong and visible but the bore is dark.  It's not fancy, but the rifle is a solid shooter.  At 200 yards, the rifle easily shoots "minute of torso" using "spam-can" ammo.  I've not shot the rifle with commercial ammo.  

Included are the bayonet, an oiler can, an ammo pouch and the bolt adjustment tool.  The sling is *not* included. 

All reasonable offers will be considered.  I'll toss in a three packs of surplus ammo so you can immediately get to the range.  

I'm open to selling on an eFA-10 or at an FFL-01 within 30-40 minutes drive of Tyngsboro.  If FFL-01, buyer picks up the transfer fee.
